    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if there's no physical signal or hidden variable, it almost sounds like the particles have some kind of secret connection or a \"rule\" they're both following that we just can't observe. is there any theory that tries to explain that \"hidden\" part, or is it just accepted that it's fundamentally weird and unexplainable?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The quest for a deeper understanding of entanglement has indeed led to the development of several theories, though none have been conclusively accepted. One of the most prominent is the Many-Worlds Interpretation, which suggests that all possible outcomes of quantum measurements are realized, each in its own separate universe. In this view, when a measurement is made, the universe splits, creating parallel universes for each possible outcome. The entangled particles exist in the same universe before the measurement and then branch into separate universes that correspond to the outcomes, preserving the entanglement without needing a hidden variable.\n\nAnother theory, decoherence, posits that quantum systems interact with their environment in such a way that their wave functions collapse into definite states, giving the appearance of entanglement. This doesn't involve hidden variables but rather the loss of quantum coherence due to these interactions, which is a natural explanation within the standard quantum mechanics framework.\n\nDespite these theories, the true nature of entanglement remains a profound mystery, and some physicists believe that a more complete theory of quantum mechanics, possibly a theory of quantum gravity, might one day provide a deeper understanding of the fundamental connections between entangled particles.",
      "source": "target",
